    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Controlled Company Exemptions Under Nasdaq Rules\n\n## (1) Board-Level and Committee-Level Independence Requirements Waived\n\nThe filing discloses four specific Nasdaq/Nasdaq Texas corporate governance requirements that the company may elect not to comply with as a controlled company:\n\n**Board-level:**\n- The requirement that **a majority of the board of directors consist of independent directors** as defined under the listing rules.\n\n**Committee-level (Nominating):**\n- The requirement that **director nominees be selected or recommended by a nominating committee composed entirely of independent directors**, with a written charter addressing the nominations process.\n\n**Committee-level (Compensation):**\n- The requirement that **the compensation committee be composed entirely of independent directors** with a written charter addressing the committee\'s purpose and responsibilities.\n\n**Committee-level (Evaluations):**\n- The requirement that **annual performance evaluations of the compensation and nominating committees be conducted.**\n\nThe company explicitly states its intent to rely on these exemptions:\n\n> "Following the completion of this offering, we intend to utilize certain of these exemptions. As a result, we do not expect to have a compensation and nominating committee that is composed entirely of independent directors or that has a committee charter that addresses all Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas requirements applicable to companies that are not controlled companies."\n\nThe compensation and nominating committee\'s expected members are **Ira Ehrenpreis, Antonio J. Gracias, and Luke Nosek**—and the filing notes that Gracias does **not** qualify as independent, confirming the reliance on the exemption. By contrast, only Ehrenpreis and Nosek are identified as satisfying the heightened independence standards for compensation committee members.\n\n---\n\n## (2) Requirements That Remain Fully Applicable\n\nDespite controlled company status, certain requirements remain in force:\n\n- **Audit committee independence:** The filing states: *"As a controlled company, we will remain subject to rules that require us to have an audit committee composed entirely of independent directors."* The expected audit committee members, **Randy Glein and Steve Jurvetson**, each qualify as independent under **Rule 10A-3 of the Exchange Act** and the Nasdaq/Nasdaq Texas listing standards. The company also commits to identifying a third audit committee member within the applicable one-year transition period.\n\n- **Audit committee financial expert requirement:** Randy Glein is expected to qualify as an "audit committee financial expert" under SEC rules implementing Section 407 of Sarbanes-Oxley.\n\n- **Code of business conduct and ethics:** The board will adopt a code compliant with applicable SEC rules and Nasdaq/Nasdaq Texas corporate governance rules.\n\n- **Corporate governance guidelines:** The company intends to adopt governance guidelines setting forth director expectations, qualification standards, committee structure, and functions.\n\n- **Nasdaq shareholder approval requirements for certain issuances:** The filing notes that issuances equal to or exceeding 20% of then-outstanding voting power or shares require shareholder approval regardless of controlled company status.\n\n---\n\n## (3) Conditioning on Continuous Controlled Company Status\n\n**Yes—the exemptions are expressly conditioned on SpaceX maintaining controlled company status.** The filing states this in two key passages:\n\n> "Additionally, we may elect to take advantage of certain other exemptions in the future **for as long as we remain a \'controlled company.\'**"\n\n> "In the event that we cease to be a \'controlled company\' and our shares continue to be listed on Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas, **we will be required to comply with all of the applicable governance requirements within the applicable transition periods.**"\n\nThe controlled company status itself is tied to Mr. Musk\'s beneficial ownership of greater than 50% of the voting power. The Class B common stock—held predominantly by Musk—elects 51% of the board. If Musk\'s voting power were to fall below 50%, the company would lose controlled company status and would need to cure any non-compliance within the applicable Nasdaq transition periods.\n\n---\n\n## (4) Locations in the Filing Where the Exemptions Are Disclosed\n\nThe specific exemptions being relied upon are disclosed in **multiple locations** throughout the prospectus:\n\n| Location | Description |\n|---|---|\n| **Prospectus summary table (cover/preamble)** | Under the "Controlled company" line item, directing readers to "Management—Controlled Company Exemption" and "Certain Relationships and Related Person Transactions." |\n| **Risk Factors section** | Discloses that following the offering, the company "will be a \'controlled company\' within the meaning of the Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas listing rules and, as a result, will qualify for and rely on exemptions from certain [requirements]." Lists all four waived requirements. |\n| **Management—Corporate Governance section (Controlled Company Exemption)** | Provides the most detailed disclosure: defines controlled company, enumerates all four exempted requirements, states intent to utilize exemptions, warns shareholders of reduced protections, and addresses transition obligations if status is lost. |\n| **Management—Corporate Governance section (Compensation and Nominating Committee)** | Specifically discloses reliance on the exemption from the independent-director and charter requirements for the compensation and nominating committee, identifying the expected committee members and their independence qualifications. |\n| **Certain Relationships and Related Person Transactions section** | Notes Mr. Musk\'s post-IPO ownership of approximately [ ]% of Class B common stock and [ ]% of total voting power, establishing the factual basis for controlled company status. |\n\nThe most comprehensive single disclosure of the specific exemptions appears in the **Corporate Governance section** under the controlled company exemption discussion, where the filing lists each waived requirement by bullet point and then states the company\'s intent to rely on them.',
