e to be a \'controlled company\' and our shares continue to be listed on Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas, **we will be required to comply with all of the applicable governance requirements within the applicable transition periods.**\\"\\n\\nControlled-company status itself is tied to Mr. Musk\'s beneficial ownership of greater than 50% of the voting power for director elections. The Class B common stock — held predominantly by Musk — elects 51% of the board. If Musk\'s voting power were to fall below 50%, SpaceX would lose controlled-company status and would be required to cure any non-compliance within the applicable Nasdaq/Nasdaq Texas transition periods.\\n\\nThe filing defines a controlled company as follows:\\n\\n> \\"Under the listing rules of Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas, a company of which more than 50% of the voting power with respect to director elections is held by another person or group of persons acting together is a \'controlled company\' and may elect not to comply with certain Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas corporate governance requirements...\\"\\n\\n### 4. Where the Filing Discloses the Specific Exemptions Being Relied Upon\\n\\nThe specific exemptions are disclosed in multiple locations throughout the prospectus:\\n\\n| Location | Description |\\n|---|---|\\n| **Prospectus summary table** | Under the \\"Controlled company\\" line item, directing readers to \\"Management—Controlled Company Exemption\\" and \\"Certain Relationships and Related Person Transactions.\\" |\\n| **Risk Factors section** | Discloses that following the offering, SpaceX \\"will be a \'controlled company\' within the meaning of the Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas listing rules and, as a result, will qualify for and rely on exemptions from certain [requirements].\\" Lists all four waived requirements. |\\n| **Management—Corporate Governance section (Controlled Company Exemption)** | Provides the most detailed disclosure: defines controlled company, enumerates all four exempted requirements, states intent to utilize exemptions, warns shareholders of reduced protections, and addresses transition obligations if status is lost. |\\n| **Management—Corporate Governance section (Compensation and Nominating Committee)** | Specifically discloses reliance on the exemption from the independent-director and charter requirements for the compensation and nominating committee, identifying the expected committee members and their independence qualifications. |\\n| **Certain Relationships and Related Person Transactions section** | Notes Mr. Musk\'s post-IPO ownership of Class B common stock and total voting power, establishing the factual basis for controlled-company status. |\\n\\nThe most comprehensive single disclosure of the specific exemptions appears in the **Corporate Governance section** under the controlled company exemption discussion, where the filing lists each waived requirement by bullet point and then states SpaceX\'s intent to rely on them.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Summary\\n\\nSpaceX will rely on four Nasdaq/Nasdaq Texas controlled-company exemptions: (1) majority-independent board, (2) independent nominating committee with charter, (3) independent compensation committee with charter, and (4) annual performance evaluations of the compensation and nominating committees. The audit committee independence requirement (Rule 10A-3), the audit committee financial expert requirement, the code of business conduct and ethics, corporate governance guidelines, and the 20% shareholder-approval rule all remain fully applicable. The exemptions are expressly conditioned on SpaceX remaining a controlled company — if it ceases to be one, it must comply with all applicable governance requirements within the applicable Nasdaq/Nasdaq Texas transition periods. The specific exemptions are disclosed primarily in the Risk Factors section and the Management—Corporate Governance section (under \\"Controlled Company Exemption\\"), with cross-references in the prospectus summary and Certain Relationships and Related Person Transactions sections.\\n\\n{\\n  \\"sources\\": [\\n    {\\n      \\"url\\": \\"https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm\\",\\n      \\"name\\": \\"SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Risk Factors; Management—Corporate Governance (Controlled Company Exemption); Certain Relationships and Related Person Transactions\\"\\n    }\\n  ]\\n}"}',
        parsed_args={
            'final_result': '## SpaceX\'s Reliance on Nasdaq Controlled-Company Exemptions\n\n### 1. Board-Level and Committee-Level Independence Requirements WAIVED\n\nThe S-1 discloses that, as a "controlled company" under the listing rules of Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas, SpaceX may elect not to comply with four specific corporate governance requirements. The filing enumerates them verbatim:\n\n1. **Board-level (majority-independent board):** The requirement that **a majority of the board of directors consist of independent directors** as defined under the listing rules.\n\n2. **Committee-level (Nominating committee):** The requirement that **director nominees be selected or recommended for the board\'s selection by a nominating committee composed entirely of independent directors**, with a written charter addressing the nominations process as required under the Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas listing rules.\n\n3. **Committee-level (Compensation committee):** The requirement that **the compensation committee be composed entirely of independent directors** with a written charter addressing the committee\'s purpose and responsibilities.\n\n4. **Committee-level (Annual evaluations):** The requirement that **annual performance evaluations of the compensation and nominating committees be conducted.**\n\nSpaceX expressly states its intent to rely on these exemptions:\n\n> "Following the completion of this offering, we intend to utilize certain of these exemptions. As a result, we do not expect to have a compensation and nominating committee that is composed entirely of independent directors or that has a committee charter that addresses all Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas requirements applicable to companies that are not controlled companies."\n\nThe expected members of the compensation and nominating committee are Ira Ehrenpreis, Antonio J. Gracias, and Luke Nosek — and the filing notes that Gracias does not qualify as independent, confirming reliance on the exemption. Only Ehrenpreis and Nosek satisfy the heightened independence standards for compensation committee members.\n\n### 2. Requirements That REMAIN Fully Applicable Regardless of Controlled-Company Status\n\nDespite controlled-company status, the following requirements remain in force:\n\n- **Audit committee independence (Rule 10A-3 / Nasdaq):** The filing states: *"As a controlled company, we will remain subject to rules that require us to have an audit committee composed entirely of independent directors."* The expected audit committee members, Randy Glein and Steve Jurvetson, each qualify as independent under Rule 10A-3 of the Exchange Act and the Nasdaq/Nasdaq Texas listing standards. SpaceX commits to identifying a third audit committee member within the applicable one-year transition period.\n\n- **Audit committee financial expert requirement:** Randy Glein is expected to qualify as an "audit committee financial expert" under SEC rules implementing Section 407 of Sarbanes-Oxley.\n\n- **Code of business conduct and ethics:** The board will adopt a code compliant with applicable SEC rules and Nasdaq/Nasdaq Texas corporate governance rules.\n\n- **Corporate governance guidelines:** SpaceX intends to adopt governance guidelines setting forth director expectations, qualification standards, committee structure, and functions.\n\n- **Nasdaq shareholder approval requirements for certain issuances:** Issuances equal to or exceeding 20% of then-outstanding voting power or shares require shareholder approval regardless of controlled-company status.\n\n### 3. Conditioning on Continuous Controlled-Company Status\n\n**Yes — the exemptions are expressly conditioned on SpaceX maintaining controlled-company status.** The filing states this in two key passages:\n\n> "Additionally, we may elect to take advantage of certain other exemptions in the future **for as long as we remain a \'controlled company.\'**"\n\n> "In the event that we cease to be a \'controlled company\' and our shares continue to be listed on Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas, **we will be required to comply with all of the applicable governance requirements within the applicable transition periods.**"\n\nControlled-company status itself is tied to Mr. Musk\'s beneficial ownership of greater than 50% of the voting power for director elections. The Class B common stock — held predominantly by Musk — elects 51% of the board. If Musk\'s voting power were to fall below 50%, SpaceX would lose controlled-company status and would be required to cure any non-compliance within the applicable Nasdaq/Nasdaq Texas transition periods.\n\nThe filing defines a controlled company as follows:\n\n> "Under the listing rules of Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas, a company of which more than 50% of the voting power with respect to director elections is held by another person or group of persons acting together is a \'controlled company\' and may elect not to comply with certain Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas corporate governance requirements..."\n\n### 4. Where the Filing Discloses the Specific Exemptions Being Relied Upon\n\nThe specific exemptions are disclosed in multiple locations throughout the prospectus:\n\n| Location | Description |\n|---|---|\n| **Prospectus summary table** | Under the "Controlled company" line item, directing readers to "Management—Controlled Company Exemption" and "Certain Relationships and Related Person Transactions." |\n| **Risk Factors section** | Discloses that following the offering, SpaceX "will be a \'controlled company\' within the meaning of the Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas listing rules and, as a result, will qualify for and rely on exemptions from certain [requirements]." Lists all four waived requirements. |\n| **Management—Corporate Governance section (Controlled Company Exemption)** | Provides the most detailed disclosure: defines controlled company, enumerates all four exempted requirements, states intent to utilize exemptions, warns shareholders of reduced protections, and addresses transition obligations if status is lost. |\n| **Management—Corporate Governance section (Compensation and Nominating Committee)** | Specifically discloses reliance on the exemption from the independent-director and charter requirements for the compensation and nominating committee, identifying the expected committee members and their independence qualifications. |\n| **Certain Relationships and Related Person Transactions section** | Notes Mr. Musk\'s post-IPO ownership of Class B common stock and total voting power, establishing the factual basis for controlled-company status. |\n\nThe most comprehensive single disclosure of the specific exemptions appears in the **Corporate Governance section** under the controlled company exemption discussion, where the filing lists each waived requirement by bullet point and then states SpaceX\'s intent to rely on them.\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\nSpaceX will rely on four Nasdaq/Nasdaq Texas controlled-company exemptions: (1) majority-independent board, (2) independent nominating committee with charter, (3) independent compensation committee with charter, and (4) annual performance evaluations of the compensation and nominating committees. The audit committee independence requirement (Rule 10A-3), the audit committee financial expert requirement, the code of business conduct and ethics, corporate governance guidelines, and the 20% shareholder-approval rule all remain fully applicable. The exemptions are expressly conditioned on SpaceX remaining a controlled company — if it ceases to be one, it must comply with all applicable governance requirements within the applicable Nasdaq/Nasdaq Texas transition periods. The specific exemptions are disclosed primarily in the Risk Factors section and the Management—Corporate Governance section (under "Controlled Company Exemption"), with cross-references in the prospectus summary and Certain Relationships and Related Person Transactions sections.\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Risk Factors; Management—Corporate Governance (Controlled Company Exemption); Certain Relationships and Related Person Transactions"\n    }\n  ]\n}'
